\begin_layout Section
Overview and Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Today, serious science is inseparable from computation: scientists spend
 the majority of their day sitting at a computer writing software in a variety
 of languages on a multitude of platforms to analyze data, solve models,
 and compute answers to pertinent questions in their field.
 Scientists have become a new type of software engineer -- a research software
 developer -- whether they like it or not.
 And, most scientists are horribly bad at programming.
 Young scientists receive no training on how to build software because the
 scientific community assumes that programming is easy to pick up for anyone
 who is smart and technical.
 This belief leads to shoddy research which often violates the scientific
 method and suffers from hidden errors as well as a lack of reproducibility,
 replicability, and openness.
 The absence of software engineering skills also limits the type of problems
 researchers can study, preventing them from working on problems with large
 computational requirements and/or datasets, both of which are often central
 challenges of working at the frontiers of science.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hacker Within at the University of Chicago (THWUC) exists to solve this
 problem by providing an organization to train young researchers in scientific
 computation through regular learning lunches and workshops.
 These efforts are based on and inspired by 
